The '''2012 Tour de France''' was the 99th edition of the [[Tour de France]]. It began with a prologue [[time trial]] in the city of [[Li<U+00E8>ge]] in [[Belgium]],<ref name=letour.fr>{{Cite web|url= http://www.letour.fr/2011/TDF/COURSE/us/actus.html#zone164890|title= THE PROVINCE OF LI<U+00C8>GE HOSTS THE GRAND DEPART 2012|publisher=letour.fr|accessdate= 29 October 2010 |date= 29 October 2010 | archiveurl= http://web.archive.org/web/20101022110152/http://www.letour.fr/2011/TDF/COURSE/us/actus.html| archivedate= 22 October 2010 | deadurl= no}}</ref><ref name=sporza.be>{{Cite web|url= http://www.sporza.be/permalink/1.894284|title=The Tour de France 2012 starts in Li<U+00E8>ge|publisher=sporza.be|accessdate=29 October 2010 |date= 29 October 2010 |language=dutch| archiveurl= http://web.archive.org/web/20101102163351/http://www.sporza.be/permalink/1.894284| archivedate= 2 November 2010 | deadurl= no}}</ref> and reached its conclusion on the [[Champs-<U+00C9>lys<U+00E9>es]] in [[Paris]].  As well as the prologue, the first two road stages took place in Belgium, and one stage finished in [[Switzerland]].

The route was accidentally leaked by the [[Amaury Sport Organisation|ASO]] on its website on 10 October 2011,<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.france-info.com/sport-cyclisme-2011-10-10-le-parcours-du-tour-de-france-2012-devoile-par-erreur-sur-le-site-d-567868-27-526.html|title=Le parcours du Tour de France-2012 d<U+00E9>voil<U+00E9> par erreur sur le site d<U+2019>ASO|accessdate=2011-10-11}}</ref> eight days before the official presentation.The route featured a total of 101.1&nbsp;km<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.eurosport.fr/cyclisme/tour-de-france/2012/5-km-de-chrono-en-plus_sto3177406/story.shtml|title=5&nbsp;km de chrono en plus
|accessdate= 25 May 2012 }}</ref> in individual time trials and three uphill finishes: [[La Planche des Belles Filles]] (stage 7), [[Les Sybelles|La Toussuire - Les Sybelles]] (stage 11) and [[Peyragudes]] (stage 17).  The [[Col du Grand Colombier]], a climb that had previously featured in the [[Crit<U+00E9>rium du Dauphin<U+00E9>]], [[Tour de l'Avenir]] and the [[Tour de l'Ain]], was included for the first time, and was among six [[hors cat<U+00E9>gorie]] rated climbs in the [[Alps]] and [[Pyrenees]]. <ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.cyclingnews.com/news/2012-tour-de-france-route-officially-presented|title=2012 Tour de France route officially presented|accessdate=11 October 2011}}</ref>

[[Bradley Wiggins]] ({{ct|SKY|2012}}) won the overall race, 3' 21" clear of compatriot and teammate [[Chris Froome]].  They became the first British riders to finish in the top three in the [[general classification]].  The [[yellow jersey]] was worn for the first week by Switzerland's [[Fabian Cancellara]] ({{ct|RNT|2012}}), who won the prologue.<ref>{{cite web|last=Benson|first=Daniel|title=Cancellara wins 2012 Tour de France prologue in Li<U+00E8>ge|url=http://www.cyclingnews.com/tour-de-france/prologue/results|work=Cycling News|publisher=Future Publishing Limited|date=30 June 2012|accessdate=22 July 2012}}</ref>  Wiggins, second in the prologue, took the leadership of the race on stage 7, the first mountainous stage, which was won by Froome,<ref>{{cite web|last=Westemeyer|first=Susan|title=Froome leads double Sky success on La Planche des Belles Filles|url=http://www.cyclingnews.com/tour-de-france/stage-7/results|work=Cycling News|publisher=Future Publishing Limited|date=7 July 2012|accessdate=22 July 2012}}</ref> and maintained his lead throughout the rest of the race, winning both the long time trials, and not losing time to his main challengers for the overall title in the mountains.  Froome came second in both the long time trials, and was alongside, or slightly ahead of, Wiggins on the mountainous stages.  Italian [[Vincenzo Nibali]] ({{ct|LIQ|2012}}) was third place overall and the only rider to consistently keep pace with Wiggins and Froome in the mountains.

The [[Points classification in the Tour de France|points classification]] for the most consistent finisher was won by Nibali's Slovakian teammate [[Peter Sagan]].  Sagan won three stages, and was second or third in four others: German sprinter [[Andr<U+00E9> Greipel]] of {{ct|LTB|2012}}, and world champion [[Mark Cavendish]], another British rider on {{ct|SKY|2012|nolink=yes}}, both also won three stages, but were less consistent in other sprints.  {{ct|EUC|2012}}'s French rider [[Thomas Voeckler]], winner of two mountainous stages and top scorer on seven successive cols, won the [[King of the Mountains]] title, and {{ct|BMC|2012}}'s American rider [[Tejay van Garderen]], in fifth place overall, won the award for the best young rider, while the team competition was won by {{ct|RNT|2012}}, and [[Chris Anker S<U+00F8>rensen]] was given the award for the most combative rider.

==Teams==
{{main|List of teams and cyclists in the 2012 Tour de France}}
All 18 teams in the [[UCI]]'s [[UCI ProTeam|Proteam]] category were entitled, and obliged, to enter the race.  Four [[UCI Professional Continental]] teams, one Dutch and three French-based, were also invited.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.letour.fr/2012/TDF/COURSE/us/actus.html#zone186563 |title=SELECTION OF TEAMS FOR TOUR DE FRANCE 2012 |publisher=letour.fr |date=6 April 2012 |accessdate=6 April 2012}}</ref>

