==Pre-race favourites==
2011 winner [[Cadel Evans]] attempted to defend his Tour title, but lost time on two key mountain stages and finished in seventh place. Runner-up [[Andy Schleck]] (and later declared [[2010 Tour de France|2010]] winner) was not in the Tour due to a fracture of the [[sacrum|sacral bone]] of his pelvis at the Crit<U+00E9>rium du Dauphin<U+00E9>.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.radioshacknissantrek.com/news/andy-scheck-sacral-fracture-out-tour-de-france|title=Andy Scheck with sacral fracture out for Tour de France|work=radioshacknissantrek.com|date=13 June 2012|accessdate=13 June 2012}}</ref> The third still-active former Tour de France winner [[Alberto Contador]] is suspended and did not start in this year's Tour.

Other former [[Grand Tour (cycling)|Grand Tour]] winners who took part in this Tour de France were: [[Denis Menchov]] ([[2009 Giro d'Italia]], and [[2005 Vuelta a Espa<U+00F1>a|2005]] and [[2007 Vuelta a Espa<U+00F1>a]]: finished 15th), [[Alexander Vinokourov]] ([[2006 Vuelta a Espana]]: finished 31st), [[Alejandro Valverde]] ([[2009 Vuelta a Espa<U+00F1>a]]: finished 20th), [[Vincenzo Nibali]] ([[2010 Vuelta a Espa<U+00F1>a]]: finished 3rd), [[Juan Jos<U+00E9> Cobo]] ([[2011 Vuelta a Espa<U+00F1>a]]: finished 30th), [[Ivan Basso]] ([[2006 Giro d'Italia]] and [[2010 Giro d'Italia]]: finished 25th), [[Michele Scarponi]] ([[2011 Giro d'Italia]]: finished 24th) and [[Ryder Hesjedal]] ([[2012 Giro d'Italia]]: withdrew injured).<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.cyclingnews.com/news/cobo-to-ride-tour-and-vuelta-in-2012|title=Cobo to ride Tour and Vuelta in 2012|work=cyclingnews.com|date=12 january 2012|accessdate=14 June 2012}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.cyclingnews.com/news/hesjedal-heads-to-tour-de-france-with-another-win-on-his-mind|title=Hesjedal heads to Tour de France with another win on his mind|work=cyclingnews.com|date=5 June 2012|accessdate=14 June 2012}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.cyclingnews.com/news/scarponi-set-to-ride-tour-de-france|title=Scarponi set to ride Tour de France|work=cyclingnews.com|date=19 June 2012|accessdate=23 June 2012}}</ref>

According to many critics before the race the favourite was the eventual winner, British rider [[Bradley Wiggins]].<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.cyclingnews.com/news/wiggins-may-not-yet-be-at-his-peak-says-holm|title=Wiggins may not yet be at his peak, says Holm|work=cyclingnews.com|date=13 June 2012|accessdate=14 June 2012}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.cyclingnews.com/news/yates-wiggins-hasnt-peaked-yet|title=Yates: Wiggins hasn<U+2019>t peaked yet|work=cyclingnews.com|date=13 June 2012|accessdate=14 June 2012}}</ref> Having finished fourth in the [[2009 Tour de France|2009 edition]] and been a podium finisher in the [[2011 Vuelta a Espa<U+00F1>a]], Wiggins had already showed good form during the season by winning the overall title in the stage races [[2012 Paris-Nice|Paris-Nice]], [[2012 Tour de Romandie|Tour de Romandie]] and the [[2012 Crit<U+00E9>rium du Dauphin<U+00E9>|Crit<U+00E9>rium du Dauphin<U+00E9>]].

